ct, including Félix Vallotton, Pierre Bonnard, Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec, Honoré Daumier, Edgar Degas, Jean-Léon Gérôme, Eugène Carrière, Charles Angrand, and Auguste and Louise Lumière. From morally and intellectually empty to sensitive, empathetic, and humane, the gawkers these artists portrayed cut across social categories. They invite the viewer’s identification, even as they appear to threaten social responsibility and the integrity of art.Delving into the ubiquity of a figure that has largely eluded attention, idling on the margins of culture and current events, Gawkers traces the emergence of social and aesthetic problems that are still with us today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArt, Frenchy19th centuryxThemes, motives. 0aSocial distance. 0aSpectators in art. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh  aAdvertising.  aAeschylus.  aAestheticism.  aAlfred Dreyfus.  aAlfred Jarry.  aAmbroise Vollard.  aAuguste Vaillant.  aBadaud.  aBenvenuto Cellini.  aCamille Mauclair.  aCaricature.  aCartoon.  aCesare Lombroso.  aChampfleury.  aCharivari.  aCharles Baudelaire.  aCharles Booth (social reformer).  aCharles Philipon.  aChester Dale.  aCompetition.  aConstantin Guys.  aCricket test.  aCrowd psychology.  aDegenerate art.  aDictionary of Received Ideas.  aDisenchantment.  aDreyfus affair.  aE. T. A. Hoffmann.  aEdgar Allan Poe.  aEdgar Degas.  aFerdinand Walsin Esterhazy.  aFine art.  aFunctional response.  aGawker.  aGeorges Seurat.  aGiacomo Meyerbeer.  aGustave Caillebotte.  aGustave Courbet.  aHerbert Marcuse.  aHonoré Daumier.  aHydra effect.  aIllustration.  aImpressionism.  aIsocline.  aJane Avril.  aJingoism.  aJournalism.  aJules Renard.  aL'Assiette au Beurre.  aL'Aurore.  aLa C